{"title_page": "Robert S. Neuwirth", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Robert Neuwirth}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Dr. Robert S. Neuwirth\n| image = Neuwirth-jumbo.jpg\n| alt = man with glasses portrait\n| caption = <!--(not needed as image is straightforward portrait)-->\n| birth_date = July 11, 1933\n| birth_place = Flora Park, New York\n| death_date = December 17, 2013\n| residence = [[New York City]], [[Tampa, Florida]], [[Englewood, New Jersey]]\n| death_place = Newark, New Jersey\n| education = [[Yale University]], Yale School of Medicine, [[Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center]]\n| known_for = Innovations in gynecologic endoscopy, real estate \n| children = Five, including [[Jessica Neuwirth]]\n}}\n'''Dr. Robert S. Neuwirth''' (July 11, 1933<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/30/us/dr-robert-neuwirth-a-pioneering-gynecologist-dies-at-80.html|title=Dr. Robert Neuwirth, a Pioneering Gynecologist, Dies at 80|last=Yardley|first=William|date=2013-12-29|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref> - December 17, 2013) was an American physician, inventor, and real estate developer. Dr. Neuwirth devoted his career to crafting and refining noninvasive practices promoting women's health. He was one of the first doctors to employ [[endoscopy]] in gynecological practice, in which a small optical instrument called an [[endoscope]] is used to examine areas tucked deep into the body. He is known as the first doctor to introduce laparoscopy to the United States, in 1968. \n\nNeuwrith is also known for his work in the pharmaceutical industry and  sold several of his patents, primarily to [[Johnson & Johnson]], between 1994 and 2003.\n\nFrom 1974 to 1991, Dr. Neuwirth acted as chairman of the Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology at [[St. Luke's\u2013Roosevelt Hospital Center|St. Lukes-Roosevelt Hospital]] in [[Manhattan]], at which time he published a critical analysis of the gynecological uses of [[hysteroscopy]]. In 1977 he was appointed as the first Babcock Professor of Obstetrics and Gynecology at [[Columbia University]]. During that tenure, he served as an examiner for the American Board of Obstetrics and Gynecology from 1982 to 1998.\n\nDr. Neuwirth contributed to at least 55 medical journals and publications in his lifetime.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vitals.com/doctors/Dr_Robert_S_Neuwirth/credentials|title=Dr. Robert S. Neuwirth Hospital Affiliations, Awards and Credentials, Obstetrician & Gynecologist, New York, NY|website=Vitals|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref>\n\n== Gynecologic endoscopy ==\nOne of Dr. Neuwirth's greatest priorities was lessening the need for [[hysterectomy]], a common gynecological surgical procedure that removes the uterus while often posing significant risks of infection and other severe complications.\n\nThe surgical discipline of gynecological endoscopy, which Dr. Neuwirth pioneered, utilizes optical instruments to help diagnose common female-specific disorders and pathologies, including but not limited to infertility and vaginal hemorrhaging. Gynecological endoscopy is performed using at least one of two methods: hysteroscopy and laparoscopy.\n\nDr. Neuwirth is credited as the first doctor to introduce [[laparoscopy]] to the United States in 1968, authoring several research articles on laparosopic sterilization and ovarian biopsies.{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}} In 1969 he introduced hysteroscopy to the American gynecological community and authored a monograph on the technique in 1974. In 1976, Dr. Neuwirth developed resectoscopic surgery of submucous fibroids, arguably the most important development in modern gynecology.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Radiological Interventions in Obstetrics and Gynaecology|last=Reidy|first=John|publisher=Springer|year=2014|isbn=3642279759|location=|pages=119|via=}}</ref> The technique enabled doctors to minimize uterine perforation.\n\nIn 1992, Dr. Neuwirth authored the first report on long-term outcome of menstrual function following hysteroscopic [[endometrial ablation]], a treatment for abnormal uterine bleeding. He is also the inventor of balloon endometrial ablation.\n\n== Selected works ==\n* ''Hysteroscopy (Major problems in obstetrics and gynecology)'', 1975\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neuwirth, Robert S.}}\n[[Category:American obstetricians]]\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:American gynecologists]]\n[[Category:American medical writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Robert Neuwirth}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Dr. Robert S. Neuwirth\n|[[File:Neuwirth-jumbo.jpg|thumb|right|Robert S. Neuwirth]]\n| birth_date = July 11, 1933\n| birth_place = Flora Park, New York\n| death_date = December 17, 2013\n| residence = [[New York City]], [[Tampa, Florida]], [[Englewood, New Jersey]]\n| death_place = Newark, New Jersey\n| education = [[Yale University]], Yale School of Medicine, [[Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center]]\n| known_for = Innovations in gynecologic endoscopy, real estate \n| children = Five, including [[Jessica Neuwirth]]\n}}\n'''Dr. Robert S. Neuwirth''' (July 11, 1933<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/30/us/dr-robert-neuwirth-a-pioneering-gynecologist-dies-at-80.html|title=Dr. Robert Neuwirth, a Pioneering Gynecologist, Dies at 80|last=Yardley|first=William|date=2013-12-29|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref> - December 17, 2013) was an American physician, inventor, and real estate developer. Dr. Neuwirth devoted his career to crafting and refining noninvasive practices promoting women's health. He was one of the first doctors to employ [[endoscopy]] in gynecological practice, in which a small optical instrument called an [[endoscope]] is used to examine areas tucked deep into the body. He is known as the first doctor to introduce laparoscopy to the United States, in 1968. \n\nNeuwrith is also known for his work in the pharmaceutical industry and  sold several of his patents, primarily to [[Johnson & Johnson]], between 1994 and 2003.\n\nFrom 1974 to 1991, Dr. Neuwirth acted as chairman of the Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology at [[St. Luke's\u2013Roosevelt Hospital Center|St. Lukes-Roosevelt Hospital]] in [[Manhattan]], at which time he published a critical analysis of the gynecological uses of [[hysteroscopy]]. In 1977 he was appointed as the first Babcock Professor of Obstetrics and Gynecology at [[Columbia University]]. During that tenure, he served as an examiner for the American Board of Obstetrics and Gynecology from 1982 to 1998.\n\nDr. Neuwirth contributed to at least 55 medical journals and publications in his lifetime.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vitals.com/doctors/Dr_Robert_S_Neuwirth/credentials|title=Dr. Robert S. Neuwirth Hospital Affiliations, Awards and Credentials, Obstetrician & Gynecologist, New York, NY|website=Vitals|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref>\n\n== Gynecologic endoscopy ==\nOne of Dr. Neuwirth's greatest priorities was lessening the need for [[hysterectomy]], a common gynecological surgical procedure that removes the uterus while often posing significant risks of infection and other severe complications.\n\nThe surgical discipline of gynecological endoscopy, which Dr. Neuwirth pioneered, utilizes optical instruments to help diagnose common female-specific disorders and pathologies, including but not limited to infertility and vaginal hemorrhaging. Gynecological endoscopy is performed using at least one of two methods: hysteroscopy and laparoscopy.\n\nDr. Neuwirth is credited as the first doctor to introduce [[laparoscopy]] to the United States in 1968, authoring several research articles on laparosopic sterilization and ovarian biopsies.{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}} In 1969 he introduced hysteroscopy to the American gynecological community and authored a monograph on the technique in 1974. In 1976, Dr. Neuwirth developed resectoscopic surgery of submucous fibroids, arguably the most important development in modern gynecology.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Radiological Interventions in Obstetrics and Gynaecology|last=Reidy|first=John|publisher=Springer|year=2014|isbn=3642279759|location=|pages=119|via=}}</ref> The technique enabled doctors to minimize uterine perforation.\n\nIn 1992, Dr. Neuwirth authored the first report on long-term outcome of menstrual function following hysteroscopic [[endometrial ablation]], a treatment for abnormal uterine bleeding. He is also the inventor of balloon endometrial ablation.\n\n== Selected works ==\n* ''Hysteroscopy (Major problems in obstetrics and gynecology)'', 1975\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neuwirth, Robert S.}}\n[[Category:American obstetricians]]\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:American gynecologists]]\n[[Category:American medical writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Akb210", "label": "safe", "comment": "added portrait", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_S._Neuwirth"}
